sh pronunciation respelling"><span style=3D"font-size:90%">BAY</span>-zh=C9=
=99n</i></a>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is a metho=
d of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_inference" title=
=3D"Statistical inference">statistical inference</a> in which <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem" title=3D"Bayes' theorem">Baye=
s' theorem</a> is used to calculate a probability of a hypothesis, given pr=
ior <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evidence" title=3D"Evidence">e=
vidence</a>, and update it as more <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Information" title=3D"Information">information</a> becomes available. Fund=
amentally, Bayesian inference uses a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Prior_probability" title=3D"Prior probability">prior distribution</a> to=
 estimate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_probability" t=
itle=3D"Posterior probability">posterior probabilities.</a> Bayesian infere=
nce is an important technique in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
tatistics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a>, and especially in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_statistics" title=3D"Mathema=
tical statistics">mathematical statistics</a>. Bayesian updating is particu=
larly important in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequential_=
analysis" title=3D"Sequential analysis">dynamic analysis of a sequence of d=
ata</a>. Bayesian inference has found application in a wide range of activi=
ties, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science" title=3D"=
Science">science</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering"=
 title=3D"Engineering">engineering</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Philosophy" title=3D"Philosophy">philosophy</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medicine" title=3D"Medicine">medicine</a>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sport" title=3D"Sport">sport</a>, and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law" title=3D"Law">law</a>. In the philos=
ophy of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_theory" title=3D"=
Decision theory">decision theory</a>, Bayesian inference is closely related=
 to subjective probability, often called "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Bayesian_probability" title=3D"Bayesian probability">Bayesian proba=
bility</a>".
</p>
