<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Asymptotic_behaviour_of_pos=
terior">Asymptotic behaviour of posterior</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_inference&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Asymptotic behaviour of posterior"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Consider the behaviour of a belief distribution as it is updated a large=
 number of times with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_=
and_identically_distributed" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Independent and=
 identically distributed">independent and identically distributed</a> trial=
s. For sufficiently nice prior probabilities, the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Bernstein%E2%80%93von_Mises_theorem" title=3D"Bernstein=E2=
=80=93von Mises theorem">Bernstein-von Mises theorem</a> gives that in the =
limit of infinite trials, the posterior converges to a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Gaussian distribution">Gaussian distribution</a> independent of the initial=
 prior under some conditions firstly outlined and rigorously proven by <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_L._Doob" title=3D"Joseph L. Doo=
b">Joseph L. Doob</a> in 1948, namely if the random variable in considerati=
on has a finite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_space"=
 title=3D"Probability space">probability space</a>. The more general result=
s were obtained later by the statistician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/David_A._Freedman_(statistician)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Da=
vid A. Freedman (statistician)">David A. Freedman</a> who published in two =
seminal research papers in 1963 <sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-12">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> and 1965 <sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-13"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 when and under what circumstances the asymptotic behaviour of posterior is=
 guaranteed. His 1963 paper treats, like Doob (1949), the finite case and c=
omes to a satisfactory conclusion. However, if the random variable has an i=
nfinite but countable <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_=
space" title=3D"Probability space">probability space</a> (i.e., correspondi=
ng to a die with infinite many faces) the 1965 paper demonstrates that for =
a dense subset of priors the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berns=
tein%E2%80%93von_Mises_theorem" title=3D"Bernstein=E2=80=93von Mises theore=
m">Bernstein-von Mises theorem</a> is not applicable. In this case there is=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almost_surely" title=3D"Almost su=
rely">almost surely</a> no asymptotic convergence. Later in the 1980s and 1=
990s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_A._Freedman_(statistici=
an)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"David A. Freedman (statistician)">Freed=
man</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persi_Diaconis" title=
=3D"Persi Diaconis">Persi Diaconis</a> continued to work on the case of inf=
inite countable probability spaces.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-1=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> To summarise, there may be insufficient trials to suppress t=
he effects of the initial choice, and especially for large (but finite) sys=
tems the convergence might be very slow.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Conjugate_priors">Conjugate=
 priors</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBaye=
sian_inference&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: C=
onjugate priors"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjugate_prior" tit=
le=3D"Conjugate prior">Conjugate prior</a></div>
<p>In parameterized form, the prior distribution is often assumed to come f=
rom a family of distributions called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Conjugate_prior" title=3D"Conjugate prior">conjugate priors</a>. The use=
fulness of a conjugate prior is that the corresponding posterior distributi=
on will be in the same family, and the calculation may be expressed in <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closed-form_expression" title=3D"Close=
d-form expression">closed form</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Estimates_of_parameters_and=
_predictions">Estimates of parameters and predictions</h3><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_inference&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Estimates of parameters and pr=
edictions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>It is often desired to use a posterior distribution to estimate a parame=
ter or variable. Several methods of Bayesian estimation select <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_tendency" title=3D"Central tendency">m=
easurements of central tendency</a> from the posterior distribution.
</p><p>For one-dimensional problems, a unique median exists for practical c=
ontinuous problems. The posterior median is attractive as a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robust_statistics" title=3D"Robust statistics">ro=
bust estimator</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-15"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>If there exists a finite mean for the posterior distribution, then t=
he posterior mean is a method of estimation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#=
cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
