<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_frequentist_statistics_a=
nd_decision_theory">In frequentist statistics and decision theory</h2><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_inference&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: In frequentist sta=
tistics and decision theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_decision_theory" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical decision theory">decision-theore=
tic</a> justification of the use of Bayesian inference was given by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham_Wald" title=3D"Abraham Wald">Abra=
ham Wald</a>, who proved that every unique Bayesian procedure is <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Admissible_decision_rule" title=3D"Admissibl=
e decision rule">admissible</a>. Conversely, every <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Admissible_decision_rule" title=3D"Admissible decision rul=
e">admissible</a> statistical procedure is either a Bayesian procedure or a=
 limit of Bayesian procedures.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bickel_&amp;_Doksum_2001,=
_page_32_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-Bickel_&amp;_Doksum_2001,_page_32-20"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>Wald characterized admissible procedures as Bayesian procedures (and=
 limits of Bayesian procedures), making the Bayesian formalism a central te=
chnique in such areas of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequenti=
st_inference" title=3D"Frequentist inference">frequentist inference</a> as =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parameter_estimation" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Parameter estimation">parameter estimation</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypothesis_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Hypothesis testing">hypothesis testing</a>, and computing <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_intervals" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Confidence intervals">confidence intervals</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesi=
an_inference#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_not=
e-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For=
 example:
</p>
<ul><li>"Under some conditions, all admissible procedures are either Bayes =
procedures or limits of Bayes procedures (in various senses). These remarka=
ble results, at least in their original form, are due essentially to Wald. =
They are useful because the property of being Bayes is easier to analyze th=
an admissibility."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bickel_&amp;_Doksum_2001,_page_32_20-=
1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_in=
ference#cite_note-Bickel_&amp;_Doksum_2001,_page_32-20"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>"In decision theory, a quite general method for proving admissibility c=
onsists in exhibiting a procedure as a unique Bayes solution."<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bay=
esian_inference#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>"In the first chapters of this work, prior distributions with finite su=
pport and the corresponding Bayes procedures were used to establish some of=
 the main theorems relating to the comparison of experiments. Bayes procedu=
res with respect to more general prior distributions have played a very imp=
ortant role in the development of statistics, including its asymptotic theo=
ry." "There are many problems where a glance at posterior distributions, fo=
r suitable priors, yields immediately interesting information. Also, this t=
echnique can hardly be avoided in sequential analysis."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_i=
nference#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>"A useful fact is that any Bayes decision rule obtained by taking a pro=
per prior over the whole parameter space must be admissible"<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes=
ian_inference#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>"An important area of investigation in the development of admissibility=
 ideas has been that of conventional sampling-theory procedures, and many i=
nteresting results have been obtained."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_no=
te-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Model_selection">Model sele=
ction</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesi=
an_inference&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: Mod=
el selection"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_model_selec=
tion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bayesian model selection">Bayesian mod=
el selection</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_information_cri=
terion" title=3D"Bayesian information criterion">Bayesian information crite=
rion</a></div>
<p>Bayesian methodology also plays a role in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Model_selection" title=3D"Model selection">model selection</a> w=
here the aim is to select one model from a set of competing models that rep=
resents most closely the underlying process that generated the observed dat=
a. In Bayesian model comparison, the model with the highest <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_probability" title=3D"Posterior probabi=
lity">posterior probability</a> given the data is selected. The posterior p=
robability of a model depends on the evidence, or <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Marginal_likelihood" title=3D"Marginal likelihood">marginal=
 likelihood</a>, which reflects the probability that the data is generated =
by the model, and on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prior_pro=
bability" title=3D"Prior probability">prior belief</a> of the model. When t=
wo competing models are a priori considered to be equiprobable, the ratio o=
f their posterior probabilities corresponds to the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Bayes_factor" title=3D"Bayes factor">Bayes factor</a>. Sin=
ce Bayesian model comparison is aimed on selecting the model with the highe=
st posterior probability, this methodology is also referred to as the maxim=
um a posteriori (MAP) selection rule <sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note=
-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> or the MAP probability rule.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#=
cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Probabilistic_programming">=
Probabilistic programming</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DBayesian_inference&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=
=3D"Edit section: Probabilistic programming"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabilistic_progra=
mming" title=3D"Probabilistic programming">Probabilistic programming</a></d=
iv>
<p>While conceptually simple, Bayesian methods can be mathematically and nu=
merically challenging. Probabilistic programming languages (PPLs) implement=
 functions to easily build Bayesian models together with efficient automati=
c inference methods. This helps separate the model building from the infere=
nce, allowing practitioners to focus on their specific problems and leaving=
 PPLs to handle the computational details for them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_infer=
ence#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-31"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_inf=
erence&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Applicati=
ons"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Statistical_data_analysis">=
Statistical data analysis</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DBayesian_inference&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=
=3D"Edit section: Statistical data analysis"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>See the separate Wikipedia entry on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Bayesian_statistics" title=3D"Bayesian statistics">Bayesian statistics=
</a>, specifically the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_st=
atistics#Statistical_modeling" title=3D"Bayesian statistics">statistical mo=
deling</a> section in that page.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computer_applications">Comp=
uter applications</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DBayesian_inference&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit =
section: Computer applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Bayesian inference has applications in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title=3D"Artificial intelligence">artifici=
al intelligence</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expert_sys=
tem" title=3D"Expert system">expert systems</a>.  Bayesian inference techni=
ques have been a fundamental part of computerized <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Pattern_recognition" title=3D"Pattern recognition">pattern =
recognition</a> techniques since the late 1950s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inferenc=
e#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> There is also an ever-growing connection betwee=
n Bayesian methods and simulation-based <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method" title=3D"Monte Carlo method">Monte Carlo</a> tech=
niques since complex models cannot be processed in closed form by a Bayesia=
n analysis, while a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphical_mode=
l" title=3D"Graphical model">graphical model</a> structure <i>may</i> allow=
 for efficient simulation algorithms like the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Gibbs_sampling" title=3D"Gibbs sampling">Gibbs sampling</a> and=
 other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metropolis%E2%80%93Hastings=
_algorithm" title=3D"Metropolis=E2=80=93Hastings algorithm">Metropolis=E2=
=80=93Hastings algorithm</a> schemes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note=
-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> Recently<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"wh=
ite-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:M=
anual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title=3D"Wikipedia:Ma=
nual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title=3D"The time period mentioned n=
ear this tag is ambiguous. (September 2018)">when?</span></a></i>]</sup> Ba=
yesian inference has gained popularity among the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Phylogenetics" title=3D"Phylogenetics">phylogenetics</a> com=
munity for these reasons; a number of applications allow many demographic a=
nd evolutionary parameters to be estimated simultaneously.
</p><p>As applied to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_c=
lassification" title=3D"Statistical classification">statistical classificat=
ion</a>, Bayesian inference has been used to develop algorithms for identif=
ying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E-mail_spam" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"E-mail spam">e-mail spam</a>. Applications which make use of=
 Bayesian inference for spam filtering include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/CRM114_(program)" title=3D"CRM114 (program)">CRM114</a>, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDSPAM&amp;action=3Dedit&=
amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"DSPAM (page does not exist)">DSPAM<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bogofilter" title=3D"Bogofilt=
er">Bogofilter</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SpamAssassin" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SpamAssassin">SpamAssassin</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SpamBayes" title=3D"SpamBayes">SpamBayes</a>, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mozilla" title=3D"Mozilla">Mozilla=
</a>, XEAMS, and others. Spam classification is treated in more detail in t=
he article on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Na%C3%AFve_Bayes=
_classifier" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Na=C3=AFve Bayes classifier">na=
=C3=AFve Bayes classifier</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solomonoff%27s_theory_of_in=
ductive_inference" title=3D"Solomonoff's theory of inductive inference">Sol=
omonoff's Inductive inference</a> is the theory of prediction based on obse=
rvations; for example, predicting the next symbol based upon a given series=
 of symbols. The only assumption is that the environment follows some unkno=
wn but computable <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_dist=
ribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probability distribution</a>. =
It is a formal inductive framework that combines two well-studied principle=
s of inductive inference: Bayesian statistics and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Occam%27s_Razor" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Occam's Raz=
or">Occam's Razor</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-35"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Reliable_sources" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Reliable sources"><span title=3D"The material near this tag m=
ay rely on an unreliable source. (September 2018)">unreliable source?</span=
></a></i>]</sup> Solomonoff's universal prior probability of any prefix <i>=
p</i> of a computable sequence <i>x</i> is the sum of the probabilities of =
all programs (for a universal computer) that compute something starting wit=
h <i>p</i>. Given some <i>p</i> and any computable but unknown probability =
distribution from which <i>x</i> is sampled, the universal prior and Bayes'=
 theorem can be used to predict the yet unseen parts of <i>x</i> in optimal=
 fashion.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ba=
yesian_inference#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Bioinformatics_and_healthca=
re_applications">Bioinformatics and healthcare applications</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_inference&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Bioinformatics and heal=
thcare applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Bayesian inference has been applied in different <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Bioinformatics" title=3D"Bioinformatics">bioinformatics</=
a> applications, including differential gene expression analysis.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-:edgr_38-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-:edgr-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Bayesian inferen=
ce is also used in a general cancer risk model, called <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_Individualized_Risk_Index" title=3D"Continu=
ous Individualized Risk Index">CIRI</a> (Continuous Individualized Risk Ind=
ex), where serial measurements are incorporated to update a Bayesian model =
which is primarily built from prior knowledge.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#=
cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-40"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cosmology_and_astrophysical=
_applications">Cosmology and astrophysical applications</h3><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_inference&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Cosmology and astrophysica=
l applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>The Bayesian approach has been central to recent progress in cosmology a=
nd astrophysical applications,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-41"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and extends=
 to a wide range of astrophysical problems, including the characterisation =
of exoplanet (such as the fitting of atmosphere for <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/K2-18b" title=3D"K2-18b">k2-18b</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-43=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inf=
erence#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>), parameter constraints with cosmological =
data,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ArXiv_1807_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-ArXiv_1807-44"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> and calibration in astrophysical experiments.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4=
5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_in=
ference#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In cosmology, it is often employed with computational techniques suc=
h as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_chain_Monte_Carlo" tit=
le=3D"Markov chain Monte Carlo">Markov chain Monte Carlo</a>(MCMC) and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nested_sampling_algorithm" title=3D"Ne=
sted sampling algorithm">Nested sampling algorithm</a> to analyse complex d=
atasets and navigate high-dimensional parameter space. A notable applicatio=
n is to the Planck 2018 CMB data for parameter inference.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-ArXiv_1807_44-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-ArXiv_1807-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
The six base cosmological parameters in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Lambda-CDM_model" title=3D"Lambda-CDM model">Lambda-CDM model</a> are=
 not predicted by a theory, but rather fitted from Cosmic microwave backgro=
und (CMB) data to a chosen model of cosmology (the Lambda-CDM model).<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The bayesian code for cosm=
ology `cobaya` <sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> sets =
up cosmological runs and interfaces cosmological likelihoods, Boltzmann cod=
e,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_=
inference#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which computes the predicted CMB aniso=
tropies for any given set of cosmological parameters, with MCMC or nested s=
ampler.
</p><p>This computational framework is not limited to the standard model, i=
t is also essential for testing alternative or extended theories of cosmolo=
gy, such as theories with early dark energy,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#=
cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> or modified gravity theories introducing addition=
al parameters beyond Lambda-CDM. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
ayesian_model_comparison" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bayesian model com=
parison">Bayesian model comparison</a> can then be employed to calculate th=
e evidence for competing models, providing a statistical basis to assess wh=
ether the data support them over the standard Lambda-CDM.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian=
_inference#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_the_courtroom">In the co=
urtroom</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBaye=
sian_inference&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: I=
n the courtroom"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jurimetrics#Bayesian=
_analysis_of_evidence" title=3D"Jurimetrics">Jurimetrics =C2=A7&nbsp;Bayesi=
an analysis of evidence</a></div>
<p>Bayesian inference can be used by jurors to coherently accumulate the ev=
idence for and against a defendant, and to see whether, in totality, it mee=
ts their personal threshold for "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
eyond_a_reasonable_doubt" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Beyond a reasonabl=
e doubt">beyond a reasonable doubt</a>".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_n=
ote-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-53"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Bayes' theorem is ap=
plied successively to all evidence presented, with the posterior from one s=
tage becoming the prior for the next. The benefit of a Bayesian approach is=
 that it gives the juror an unbiased, rational mechanism for combining evid=
ence. It may be appropriate to explain Bayes' theorem to jurors in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_rule" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Bayes' rule">odds form</a>, as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Betting_odds" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Betting odds">betting odds</=
a> are more widely understood than probabilities. Alternatively, a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gambling_and_information_theory" title=3D=
"Gambling and information theory">logarithmic approach</a>, replacing multi=
plication with addition, might be easier for a jury to handle.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ebits2c.png" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/2/2c/Ebits2c.png/250px-Ebits2c.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" he=
ight=3D"264" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"380" data-file-he=
ight=3D"401"></a><figcaption>Adding up evidence</figcaption></figure>
<p>If the existence of the crime is not in doubt, only the identity of the =
culprit, it has been suggested that the prior should be uniform over the qu=
alifying population.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-55"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 For example, if 1,000 people could have committed the crime, the prior pro=
bability of guilt would be 1/1000.
</p><p>The use of Bayes' theorem by jurors is controversial. In the United =
Kingdom, a defence <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expert_witness"=
 title=3D"Expert witness">expert witness</a> explained Bayes' theorem to th=
e jury in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regina_versus_Denis_J=
ohn_Adams" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Regina versus Denis John Adams">R=
 v Adams</a></i>. The jury convicted, but the case went to appeal on the ba=
sis that no means of accumulating evidence had been provided for jurors who=
 did not wish to use Bayes' theorem. The Court of Appeal upheld the convict=
ion, but it also gave the opinion that "To introduce Bayes' Theorem, or any=
 similar method, into a criminal trial plunges the jury into inappropriate =
and unnecessary realms of theory and complexity, deflecting them from their=
 proper task."
</p><p>Gardner-Medwin<sup id=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-56"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 argues that the criterion on which a verdict in a criminal trial should be=
 based is <i>not</i> the probability of guilt, but rather the <i>probabilit=
y of the evidence, given that the defendant is innocent</i> (akin to a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequentist" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Frequentist">frequentist</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/P-value" title=3D"P-value">p-value</a>). He argues that if the posterior p=
robability of guilt is to be computed by Bayes' theorem, the prior probabil=
ity of guilt must be known. This will depend on the incidence of the crime,=
 which is an unusual piece of evidence to consider in a criminal trial. Con=
sider the following three propositions:
</p>
<dl><dd><i>A</i> =E2=80=93 the known facts and testimony could have arisen =
if the defendant is guilty.</dd>
<dd><i>B</i> =E2=80=93 the known facts and testimony could have arisen if t=
he defendant is innocent.</dd>
<dd><i>C</i> =E2=80=93 the defendant is guilty.</dd></dl>
<p>Gardner-Medwin argues that the jury should believe both <i>A</i> and not=
-<i>B</i> in order to convict. <i>A</i> and not-<i>B</i> implies the truth =
of <i>C</i>, but the reverse is not true. It is possible that <i>B</i> and =
<i>C</i> are both true, but in this case he argues that a jury should acqui=
t, even though they know that they will be letting some guilty people go fr=
ee. See also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lindley%27s_paradox" =
title=3D"Lindley's paradox">Lindley's paradox</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Bayesian_epistemology">Baye=
sian epistemology</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DBayesian_inference&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit =
section: Bayesian epistemology"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_epistemology" title=3D=
"Bayesian epistemology">Bayesian epistemology</a> is a movement that advoca=
tes for Bayesian inference as a means of justifying the rules of inductive =
logic.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Popper" title=3D"Karl =
Popper">Karl Popper</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_=
Miller_(philosopher)" title=3D"David Miller (philosopher)">David Miller</a>=
 have rejected the idea of Bayesian rationalism, i.e. using Bayes rule to m=
ake epistemological inferences:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-57" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-57"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> It is prone to the same <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Vicious_circle" title=3D"Vicious circle">vicious circle</a> as any other <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justificationism" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Justificationism">justificationist</a> epistemology, because =
it presupposes what it attempts to justify. According to this view, a ratio=
nal interpretation of Bayesian inference would see it merely as a probabili=
stic version of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falsifiability" ti=
tle=3D"Falsifiability">falsification</a>, rejecting the belief, commonly he=
ld by Bayesians, that high likelihood achieved by a series of Bayesian upda=
tes would prove the hypothesis beyond any reasonable doubt, or even with li=
kelihood greater than 0.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other">Other</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_inference&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Other"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ul><li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_method" tit=
le=3D"Scientific method">scientific method</a> is sometimes interpreted as =
an application of Bayesian inference. In this view, Bayes' rule guides (or =
should guide) the updating of probabilities about <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Hypothesis" title=3D"Hypothesis">hypotheses</a> conditional=
 on new observations or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experiment=
" title=3D"Experiment">experiments</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_no=
te-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> The Bayesian inference has also been applied to treat <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_scheduling" title=3D"Stoc=
hastic scheduling">stochastic scheduling</a> problems with incomplete infor=
mation by Cai et al. (2009).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cai_et_al._2009_59-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#=
cite_note-Cai_et_al._2009-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_search_theory" title=
=3D"Bayesian search theory">Bayesian search theory</a> is used to search fo=
r lost objects.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference_in_phylogen=
y" title=3D"Bayesian inference in phylogeny">Bayesian inference in phylogen=
y</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_tool_for_methylation_=
analysis" title=3D"Bayesian tool for methylation analysis">Bayesian tool fo=
r methylation analysis</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_approaches_to_brain_f=
unction" title=3D"Bayesian approaches to brain function">Bayesian approache=
s to brain function</a>  investigate the brain as a Bayesian mechanism.</li=
>
<li>Bayesian inference in ecological studies<sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#=
cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-61"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup></li>
<li>Bayesian inference is used to estimate parameters in stochastic chemica=
l kinetic models<sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Bayesian inference in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Econophy=
sics" title=3D"Econophysics">econophysics</a> for currency or prediction of=
 trend changes in financial quotations<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_not=
e-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference_in_marketin=
g" title=3D"Bayesian inference in marketing">Bayesian inference in marketin=
g</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference_in_motor_le=
arning" title=3D"Bayesian inference in motor learning">Bayesian inference i=
n motor learning</a></li>
<li>Bayesian inference is used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Probabilistic_numerics" title=3D"Probabilistic numerics">probabilistic nume=
rics</a> to solve numerical problems</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Bayes_and_Bayesian_inferenc=
e">Bayes and Bayesian inference</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_inference&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" =
title=3D"Edit section: Bayes and Bayesian inference"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The problem considered by Bayes in Proposition&nbsp;9 of his essay, "<a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/An_Essay_Towards_Solving_a_Problem_in=
_the_Doctrine_of_Chances" title=3D"An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in th=
e Doctrine of Chances">An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine o=
f Chances</a>", is the posterior distribution for the parameter <i>a</i> (t=
he success rate) of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_d=
istribution" title=3D"Binomial distribution">binomial distribution</a>.<sup=
 class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowra=
p;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed"=
 title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs refere=
nces to reliable sources. (August 2010)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</s=
up>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_inference&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_statistic=
s#Bayesian_statistics" title=3D"History of statistics">History of statistic=
s =C2=A7&nbsp;Bayesian statistics</a></div>
<p>The term <i>Bayesian</i> refers to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Thomas_Bayes" title=3D"Thomas Bayes">Thomas Bayes</a> (1701=E2=80=93176=
1), who proved that probabilistic limits could be placed on an unknown even=
t.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>   However, it was =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre-Simon_Laplace" title=3D"Pie=
rre-Simon Laplace">Pierre-Simon Laplace</a> (1749=E2=80=931827) who introdu=
ced (as Principle VI) what is now called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem" title=3D"Bayes' theorem">Bayes' theorem</a> and us=
ed it to address problems in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celes=
tial_mechanics" title=3D"Celestial mechanics">celestial mechanics</a>, medi=
cal statistics, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reliability_(stati=
stics)" title=3D"Reliability (statistics)">reliability</a>, and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jurisprudence" title=3D"Jurisprudence">jurisp=
rudence</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stigler1986_65-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-Stigler198=
6-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Early Bayesian inference, which used uniform priors follo=
wing Laplace's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principle_of_insuff=
icient_reason" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Principle of insufficient rea=
son">principle of insufficient reason</a>, was called "<a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_probability" title=3D"Inverse probability">inv=
erse probability</a>" (because it <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Inductive_reasoning" title=3D"Inductive reasoning">infers</a> backwards fro=
m observations to parameters, or from effects to causes<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Fienberg2006_66-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-Fienberg2006-66"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>). After the =
1920s, "inverse probability" was largely supplanted  by a collection of met=
hods that came to be called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freque=
ntist_statistics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Frequentist statistics">fr=
equentist statistics</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Fienberg2006_66-1" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_n=
ote-Fienberg2006-66"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 20th century, the ideas of Laplace were further developed in =
two different directions, giving rise to <i>objective</i> and <i>subjective=
</i> currents in Bayesian practice. In the objective or "non-informative" c=
urrent, the statistical analysis depends on only the model assumed, the dat=
a analyzed,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bernardo2005_67-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-Bernardo20=
05-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> and the method assigning the prior, which differs from o=
ne objective Bayesian practitioner to another. In the subjective or "inform=
ative" current, the specification of the prior depends on the belief (that =
is, propositions on which the analysis is prepared to act), which can summa=
rize information from experts, previous studies, etc.
</p><p>In the 1980s, there was a dramatic growth in research and applicatio=
ns of Bayesian methods, mostly attributed to the discovery of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_chain_Monte_Carlo" title=3D"Markov chain=
 Monte Carlo">Markov chain Monte Carlo</a> methods, which removed many of t=
he computational problems, and an increasing interest in nonstandard, compl=
ex applications.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wolpert2004_68-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-Wolper=
t2004-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> Despite growth of Bayesian research, most undergradua=
te teaching is still based on frequentist statistics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Be=
rnardo2006_69-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Bayesian_inference#cite_note-Bernardo2006-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Nonetheless, B=
ayesian methods are widely accepted and used, such as for example in the fi=
eld of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_learning" title=3D"=
Machine learning">machine learning</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bishop2007_70-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_infe=
rence#cite_note-Bishop2007-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
